* Establish Hydra - SOTA config organization for large-scale data science projects
    Hydra solves several problems:
    - brings order into growingly complex benchmark pipeline by uniting configs file into one place: /conf
    - config file are all living in the same directory (conf) but are sub-divided into smaller config files that hierarchically sourced from each other
    - running experiments doesnt require changes in any python script, instead a final 'experiment' config file only lists the diverging settings from the default files
    - little adjustments are also possible in the terminal
    - multiruns (different datasets, seeds, models, or evaluations (loyocy, rolling)) are nicely handled by setting in the terminal or directly in the config files
    - hydra creates a run-directory that incorporates everything in one place for
     * reproducibility (config files)
     * debugging (log files)
     Extendable to:
     * results (prediction csv)
     * models (.pkl or .pt)
     * hyperparameter exploration (optuna study)
     * for the future: MLflow for training supervision

* rethink dataset & model class for user friendliness & efficiency
    DATASET:
        Introduction and Problem Statement:
      The dataset class represents the structured representation of a dataset including target and feature data,
      However, it is not build for efficient utilization in the ML context.
      A compute-efficient implementation has one key challenge - the diversity of its underlying data:
      a data unites different sources with varying temporal resolution. Secondly the varying crop seasons create
      variations in time-series length as well.
      Those two aspects are the reason why the dataset class is not compatible with with one of the common data structures
      such as pd.Dataframe, torch.Tensor or HDF5

        Solution Ideas:
      Respecting the required data input format two separate solutions are desirable
      1. TorchDataset: a fixed time-series sequence-length (e.g. 200 days) would enable a tensor representation of each data source (xarray or torch.tensor)
            This Dataclass already exists and would need to be altered.
      2. PandasDataset (or TabDataset): a feature preprocessing step, before modeling happens, creates a tabular dataformat (dataframe)
            This class would be new and similarly to TorchDataset inherits from Dataset
            It should have an easy methode to produce X and y, such as .make_X_y()
            Ready to feed into ML models such as Sklearn, XGBoost, LightGBM, TabPFN, ....

        Implementation Idea:
      The dataset creation in the current code works by executing Dataset.load() which mainly utilizes functions from configured.py
      At its core this is a data-factory that itself deserves a class. The DataFactory (data_factory.py) accepts a config object to
      build a dataset. Hydra enables input type checking by writing structured dataclasses (see DatasetConfig in cybench/config.py)
      In the new implementation a dataset is now built by executing: dataset = DataFactory(cfg.dataset).build()

      The next step it to define the data handling dependent on the desired architecture.
      I see two possibilities:
      1. Have a separate 'process' config block for transforming the dataset into TorchDataset or PandasDataset
      2. Incorporate the processing in the dataset config block and let the DataFactory build features or tensors while loading the data

      Lets discuss pros/cons of both ideas:
      1:
      + Respects the original cy-bench code -> less implementation work
      + semantic separation of data sourcing and processing
      - inherits some inefficiencies of the original dataset implementation
      - such as memory overloading when sourcing large datasets no matter the feature design
      2:
      + data processing could directly following after data loading, which potentially saves a lot of working memory (crucial for people experimenting with tabular feature data)
      + feature selection and feature design could live in the same config file (e.g. see cybench\conf\dataset\temporal\simple_aggregate.yaml)
      + main script loads and processes data in a single line
      - implementation diverges from original cy-bench code -> takes much more time than idea 1

      Overall I tend to prefer option 2 because of efficiency and a light-weight experience for users with hardware limitations.
      Due to the high implementation cost (time), an in-depth discussion and planing would be best to proceed.


