3. Implement Hydra
    Following the hydra logic - all configurations live under the cybench/conf/ folder.
    Subfolders such as dataset, model or validation represent config groups that are sourced and
    hierarchically orchestrated by the central conf/config.yaml file.
    This yaml file is accessed by an executable script (such as hydra_example.yaml) to perform an experiment.
    This script with hydra backbone will automatically construct the following folder structure under the /output folder :
    /output
        /my-experiment-name # research-level-folder: defined in config.py
            /wheat_FR_ridge_loyocv_20251111_1606 # run-level-folder: also defined in config.py
                /.hydra # created by hydra to log run configurations. See https://hydra.cc/docs/tutorials/basic/running_your_app/working_directory/
                    config.yaml: A dump of the user specified configuration
                    hydra.yaml: A dump of the Hydra configuration
                    overrides.yaml: The command line overrides used
                # TODO: not yet implemented:
                # Idea: each separate test set (e.g. from a loyocv) should get its own subfolder
                # to store results, models and optuna studies
                /loyocv_2002
                    results.csv
                    model.pkl
                    optuna_study.pkl
                    model_cfg.yaml
                /loyocv_2003
                ...
            /maize_US_ridge_loyocv_20251107_1257
            ...

    Using hydra:
    1. Simple run: poetry run python hydra_example.py
        # Executes a single run with the default configs in conf/config.yaml
    2. Manipulate run: poetry run python hydra_example.py model=lightgbm
        # overwrite the runs configuration with your own values or other predefined yaml files
    3. Multi-run: poetry run python hydra_example.py -m dataset.country=DE,NL model=ridge,lightgbm
        # automatically creates and executes multiple runs. The command above create four runs sequentially, covering all combinations
    4. Reproducing run: poetry run python hydra_example.py --config-path ..\output\experiment_name\run_name\.hydra
        # Simply switching the config-path will load the configurations of a previous run

